    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2727492100" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2727492100" />
    <a title="guzump" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/60037554-guzump"><img alt="guzump" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1556080887p2/60037554.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2727492100?book_show_action=true">May 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="guzump" class="user" itemprop="url" name="guzump" href="/user/show/60037554-guzump">guzump</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/60037554-guzump?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/60037554-guzump?shelf=reviewed-books">reviewed-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2727492100" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1288430208448737348">I must say, this book was quite interesting even if the character of Ibn Battuta is questionable at times (casually marrying and divorcing, owning multiple slaves but condemning women in Africa for befriending men yea Idk); of course, this was the middle ages so some of Ibn Battuta’s practices and attitudes can be overlooked I guess. <br/><br/>I’m surprised by Ibn Battuta’s attitude towards women in different places across the Muslim world; in particular, places where women did not veil themselves or wher</span>
  <span id="freeText1288430208448737348" style="display:none">I must say, this book was quite interesting even if the character of Ibn Battuta is questionable at times (casually marrying and divorcing, owning multiple slaves but condemning women in Africa for befriending men yea Idk); of course, this was the middle ages so some of Ibn Battuta’s practices and attitudes can be overlooked I guess. <br /><br />I’m surprised by Ibn Battuta’s attitude towards women in different places across the Muslim world; in particular, places where women did not veil themselves or where men and women interacted liberally (by Ibn Battuta’s standards) seems to really surprise him despite being such an extensive traveller. Ibn Battuta is also often startled at non-Muslims (or infidels as he refers to them) treating him with kindness, which really makes it seem that he is not too difficult to surprise. Ibn Battuta often cites miracles of various sheikhs, which are questionable to say the least. His casual attitude towards violence and slavery is also intriguing.<br /><br />Ibn Battuta displays a vast knowledge of the places he visits, knowing distinctive details of their history which are mostly accurate. He also seems to have standards for information he accepts as being credible, often citing where he learned his information and whether or not the source was reliable. He was no doubt a knowledgeable man, which is testimony to the Islamic civilization’s dedication to seeking knowledge and learning during it’s golden age (or during the decline of the civilization in this case). Learned people are treated with reverence throughout the lands he visits, again showing how knowledge was both valued and held in high esteem. Charity and hospitality across various regions also seems to be common and a highly esteemed virtue.<br /><br />What is particularly interesting is how the Islamic empire, full of diverse groups of people and varying cultures, is united through just the religion of Islam. The people Ibn Battuta encounters all have different cultural practices and norms, but adhere to the universal concepts and practices of Islamic tradition. He is able to find hospitality almost everywhere he goes, and there is a sense of kinship and community amongst different peoples.<br /><br />The book was entertaining overall, funny at times and made me raise my eyebrows once or twice (description of a particular court woman’s vagina); it provided an interesting perspective into a different time period and civilization.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1288430208448737348" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


