<div id="review_4018029561" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4018029561" />
    <a title="Dylan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/128220856-dylan"><img alt="Dylan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610347410p2/128220856.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4018029561?book_show_action=true">May 23, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dylan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dylan" href="/user/show/128220856-dylan">Dylan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4018029561" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13556745230902351764">While being swamped with historical reads for my history class, I was force-fed a gem. The travels of Ibn Battuta is the Arab equivalent of Marco Polo but much more traveled. Ibn Battuta was a world traveler of unparalleled experience at the time. He traveled all over the world and documented the people and places he went. It is a very enjoyable read compared to Marco Polo and Diary of Margery Kempe and would recommend it to anyone with the enjoyment of history or travel. 3.8/5</span>

          </span>
        </div>


